Content:: Cladocyclus (derived from the Greek κλάδος/kládos ("branch") and κύκλος/kýklos ("circle")[1]) is an extinct genus of Ichthyodectidae. It was a predatory fish of about 1.20 metres (3.9 ft) in length, found in the Albian Romualdo and Crato Formations of the Araripe Basin in northeastern Brazil.[2] A new species, Cladocyclus pankowskii, was discovered in the Cenomanian Akfabou Formation of Morocco in 2007,[3] and in the Upper Plattenkalk of Italy.[4] The species Cladocyclus geddesi is known from the Winton Formation of Australia.[5] Cladocyclus gardneri Fossil in Vienna    This article about a prehistoric ray-finned fish is a stub.
